1
00:00:00,875 --> 00:00:30,544
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah Homies to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

2
00:00:36,734 --> 00:00:48,265
So I wanted to just continue for another session the hindrances, just to go into perhaps a little bit more detail.

3
00:00:49,546 --> 00:00:55,654
And this evening I wanted to investigate deliciousness.

4
00:00:56,514 --> 00:01:00,918
And the two areas, the three areas,

5
00:01:02,332 --> 00:01:17,337
that you can look at particularly is the erotic, the romantic and love.

6
00:01:19,141 --> 00:01:23,807
I call it the erotic, not lust.

7
00:01:23,826 --> 00:01:26,890
Lust is our relationship to the erotic.

8
00:01:27,992 --> 00:01:35,340
The erotic and the romantic are just part and parcel of the loveliness of our lives, occasionally.

9
00:01:38,444 --> 00:01:43,090
And the erotic, just to think about that for a minute,

10
00:01:44,656 --> 00:01:51,125
So that's really to do with some sort of physical attraction towards another person.

11
00:01:52,367 --> 00:01:56,852
And it only happens between certain people.

12
00:01:56,873 --> 00:02:00,177
You don't feel normally erotic to everybody you meet.

13
00:02:00,697 --> 00:02:01,560
It would be exhausting.

14
00:02:03,441 --> 00:02:09,009
So there's that case of something very particular and...

15
00:02:09,530 --> 00:02:23,706
As you know, it's said that, generally speaking, if you abstract, if you separate out the erotic from the romantic from love, then it becomes a bit like eating.

16
00:02:25,028 --> 00:02:28,231
And in itself, it's a sort of empty experience.

17
00:02:29,413 --> 00:02:31,475
It loses meaning when you just do it by itself.

18
00:02:32,377 --> 00:02:37,984
Whenever I say this, I'm always reminded of Woody Allen's little crack, where he said...

19
00:02:38,858 --> 00:02:41,823
Just sex is an empty experience.

20
00:02:41,842 --> 00:02:43,265
But as empty experiences go.

21
00:02:46,211 --> 00:03:02,199
So, as usual, when you look at anything which is delightful, it's either because we like it, quite obviously, we like to indulge in it, it brings, as it were, immediate sense of happiness.

22
00:03:03,800 --> 00:03:04,540
That's the point.

23
00:03:04,561 --> 00:03:05,582
It brings happiness.

24
00:03:07,224 --> 00:03:18,181
The whole point about the erotic, the romantic, and love in the general sense, not the true meta, I mean love as attachment, is that it brings joy.

25
00:03:18,201 --> 00:03:19,563
It brings joy to the heart.

26
00:03:21,265 --> 00:03:22,647
It's a lovely experience.

27
00:03:26,754 --> 00:03:33,063
But the other side of it is, as usual, that we may also be using it to escape something.

28
00:03:33,550 --> 00:03:34,991
That's the point.

29
00:03:35,012 --> 00:03:40,518
So that we are seeking entertainment to escape something that we don't like.

30
00:03:41,359 --> 00:03:55,794
So things like such a very obvious and loud sensual experience, such as sex, is something that you can get lost in and forget the worries of your life.

31
00:03:56,500 --> 00:04:04,795
So there's always this duality with anything that we enjoy in terms of the self, in terms of how we relate to it.

32
00:04:05,417 --> 00:04:07,741
Part of it is just sheer indulgence.

33
00:04:07,822 --> 00:04:08,282
We like it.

34
00:04:08,682 --> 00:04:12,229
And it creates a lovely feeling in the heart.

35
00:04:12,250 --> 00:04:15,977
And the other side is that we may be running away from something.

36
00:04:17,509 --> 00:04:38,295
So once we have that clear in mind, with anything that we indulge in, in those two parts, then as it were, as you watch that indulgence, as it fades away, don't be surprised that underneath it there lies maybe grief, anxiety, anything that you're pushing away.

37
00:04:39,377 --> 00:04:43,461
So that these pleasant things can be used to suppress just as anything else.

38
00:04:43,482 --> 00:04:45,423
So we talked about sleep,

39
00:04:45,504 --> 00:04:47,411
as a lovely way to suppress things.

40
00:04:47,732 --> 00:04:56,680
So here, anything which is enjoyable can be used just to push it away, just gently push it away, to ignore it, for it not to be there.

41
00:04:58,634 --> 00:05:18,572
And because the sexual energy is so related to life, to the life force, any time that death appears or anything like that, there's a great desire to run that way and to reinforce the fact that there is life.

42
00:05:23,516 --> 00:05:26,699
Interestingly enough, I picked up a quote from William Blake.

43
00:05:27,288 --> 00:05:30,172
the road of excess leads to the palace of wisdom.

44
00:05:31,735 --> 00:05:32,456
You see?

45
00:05:32,475 --> 00:05:50,444
So remember that in the Buddha's life, we saw how all that loveliness that he was experiencing with his dancing girls and all that sort of stuff, and presumably his drinking, and the good time, having a good time, that in the end, it's like squeezing blood from a stone.

46
00:05:51,105 --> 00:05:55,692
Like it loses its buzz, basically.

47
00:05:55,672 --> 00:05:57,918
And there comes that weariness with it.

48
00:05:58,800 --> 00:06:05,055
And remember we, and I'll mention again towards the end, there is a distinction to be made between weariness and boredom.

49
00:06:07,521 --> 00:06:13,055
Weariness is that coming to the end of seeking happiness in that place.

50
00:06:14,014 --> 00:06:31,752
boredom is just that you're fed up with it for a while you need a break you need a fast you need a diet and then you can get back to it again refreshed so boredom is just a as we say coming from overindulgence and then but then you still want to get back to it once the hunger for it arises

51
00:06:33,504 --> 00:06:41,432
So in our meditation, of course, it can be, if you don't watch it, these thoughts around lust can be really obsessive.

52
00:06:42,233 --> 00:06:52,384
And we have to be extraordinarily patient with that and just keep coming off them and back into the body and just feel the excitement, feel what's actually happening there.

53
00:06:53,105 --> 00:07:00,694
And that business of really acknowledging what's going on, you see, sometimes you might think, well, we're too old for this, we shouldn't be thinking these things.

54
00:07:02,293 --> 00:07:03,134
But you're never too old.

55
00:07:04,516 --> 00:07:09,185
I think it was Pope John XXIII.

56
00:07:10,165 --> 00:07:18,920
I just remember a quote from him where he said the loveliness of being, I think he was 85 or something, was that the flesh had finally quietened.

57
00:07:21,843 --> 00:07:27,593
So you can expect to be harassed by this sort of thing until who knows when.

58
00:07:29,733 --> 00:07:43,353
So it's a case of being very quick with that because remember that when a thought arises and carries on, there's some force behind it which the Buddha called cetana.

59
00:07:44,336 --> 00:07:46,939
And that force, remember, is not the intention.

60
00:07:46,980 --> 00:07:48,521
Force is just a force.

61
00:07:48,682 --> 00:07:50,425
It's just an energy form.

62
00:07:50,404 --> 00:07:53,771
It's the same as when you throw a stone up into the air.

63
00:07:54,392 --> 00:07:57,319
As far as I know, they still don't quite know what it is.

64
00:07:58,040 --> 00:07:59,343
That makes the stone keep going.

65
00:07:59,944 --> 00:08:01,648
But we call it force.

66
00:08:02,430 --> 00:08:06,016
So there is something which takes...

67
00:08:05,997 --> 00:08:11,423
That which is a thought in the head, just an idea, a wish, a desire, an intention.

68
00:08:11,543 --> 00:08:17,048
See, that's why we're also being very careful to note intentions and it suddenly flips and you're away.

69
00:08:17,468 --> 00:08:17,790
It's gone.

70
00:08:18,329 --> 00:08:21,012
You're either doing something or you're thinking something or you're saying something.

71
00:08:21,994 --> 00:08:24,117
And remember, at that point, it's become an action.

72
00:08:24,297 --> 00:08:25,137
That's a karma.

73
00:08:25,158 --> 00:08:28,221
And therefore, you are reinforcing your conditioning.

74
00:08:28,901 --> 00:08:34,687
So here, if we're not very quick with these delicious thoughts, then they just run away and you've had it.

75
00:08:35,613 --> 00:08:39,177
And then it takes a time, you see, then it takes time because you've re-empowered that.

76
00:08:40,116 --> 00:08:47,644
A good metaphor for that are people who suffer from drink problems, alcoholics.

77
00:08:48,586 --> 00:09:00,597
They can be off for so long and then maybe just out of weakness or a little bit of hubris, a little bit of pride, thinking they're now above it.

78
00:09:01,337 --> 00:09:04,100
And it's just that one drink and off they go.

79
00:09:04,638 --> 00:09:07,631
because it's re-empowering an old habit.

80
00:09:07,652 --> 00:09:12,133
Of course, in that case, there's a physical element, but it's the same with smoking.

81
00:09:12,181 --> 00:09:16,385
even though there's a physical element too that people can be off smoking for a long time.

82
00:09:16,865 --> 00:09:26,817
And then just when they feel a bit down or when they're in the wrong company, they just take that one cigarette and then they're surprised how difficult it is, how suddenly that whole engine is restarted.

83
00:09:27,977 --> 00:09:42,153
So if you see these thoughts coming up, to be very quick with them and come back and just think about what that thought is doing and bring yourself back to the body

84
00:09:43,298 --> 00:09:54,193
Now, there is an exercise that you can do, which we did partly, for those of you who were here for my New Age Healing session.

85
00:09:55,515 --> 00:10:03,727
And there you actually take the image that you've got towards which you find erotic, you see.

86
00:10:03,768 --> 00:10:07,212
So it's not lust yet, it's only lust when you indulge it.

87
00:10:07,581 --> 00:10:13,594
So as soon as you see an image which is erotic, to actually begin to take the skin off.

88
00:10:13,614 --> 00:10:17,601
Look at the parts, just see that in fact, you know, we say beauty is only skin deep.

89
00:10:18,484 --> 00:10:27,581
And when you do that, then if you do it to parts which naturally raise a sense of disgust, you don't have to make yourself vomit, you understand.

90
00:10:27,562 --> 00:10:50,952
when you just raise that little bit of disgust then you'll see the mind balances itself and what we're trying to do with that exercise is to get the mind to be conditioned so that as soon as a lustful thought comes up the mind itself will change it for you you can make that a habit in the mind to do that

91
00:10:51,524 --> 00:10:58,254
And by doing that, you're undermining that process of spinning off onto these thoughts.

92
00:11:01,698 --> 00:11:05,605
If you end up being disgusted all the time, then you have to stop it.

93
00:11:07,268 --> 00:11:08,149
Because that's not the point.

94
00:11:08,349 --> 00:11:12,115
The point isn't to end up with disgust for the human body.

95
00:11:12,668 --> 00:11:16,798
It's just a little trick that we can play to make the mind flip, you see.

96
00:11:17,701 --> 00:11:22,695
And, I mean, I've practiced this myself, and it definitely works, I can assure you of that.

97
00:11:25,982 --> 00:11:55,129
and you have to be slightly careful with it too because you can be slightly unwittingly you can be suppressing see that's another point that we have to be careful of all we're thinking about is thoughts and then we have to get down to the root feeling which is that desire to be at that place which gives us so much pleasure so you have to be quite careful with the old suppression which we know from Freud becomes twisted and ends up in all sorts of peculiar behaviour

98
00:11:56,357 --> 00:12:13,320
So the thing is that what we want to do with sexual energy, or what we want to do in terms of the spiritual life, is to withdraw the unnecessary energy that we ought to have around sex.

99
00:12:16,371 --> 00:12:22,532
And there's a word that, I don't know, you never hear it these days.

100
00:12:23,153 --> 00:12:29,232
It's got a bad name because I think it was confused with suppression.

101
00:12:30,073 --> 00:12:32,576
And that word is sublimation, to sublimate.

102
00:12:33,418 --> 00:12:36,221
In science, I looked it up, I don't know anything about science.

103
00:12:36,543 --> 00:12:43,511
In science, it means when a solid evaporates immediately into air, into a gas.

104
00:12:43,812 --> 00:12:46,836
There's a special word, sublimate.

105
00:12:46,856 --> 00:12:59,254
And to sublimate means, in terms of your energy, is to divert unskillful impulses or unskillful desires into something which is skillful.

106
00:13:00,196 --> 00:13:20,466
So if we have an image of the way the mind works as just an energy system which coagulates, forms a tightness around a particular idea and spins around it like a whirlwind, and that's all we're talking about.

107
00:13:20,850 --> 00:13:21,751
We just talk about energy.

108
00:13:22,033 --> 00:13:39,578
And if I can draw that energy away, as it were, to something which, shall we say, is more useful or even expresses that in a sublimated form, then what I get is poetry, art, music.

109
00:13:40,600 --> 00:13:42,342
I don't have to go that way.

110
00:13:42,883 --> 00:13:49,373
I can draw that energy away and put it into some loving energy, some compassionate energy.

111
00:13:49,554 --> 00:13:57,326
Now, you just have to be slightly careful with that because you've also got to acknowledge that whirlwind.

112
00:13:57,447 --> 00:14:08,883
So if you don't acknowledge the whirlwind, then you think you might be putting your thoughts in better places, but you're not acknowledging this turbulence.

113
00:14:09,224 --> 00:14:10,284
So that turbulence remains.

114
00:14:10,846 --> 00:14:18,297
So you have to acknowledge the turbulence, feel the turbulence, and then cajole yourself to draw the energy into something which is more skillful.

115
00:14:19,441 --> 00:14:22,688
and there's that transformation going on.

116
00:14:22,710 --> 00:14:28,684
Now this of course became the root understanding of Tantra.

117
00:14:28,865 --> 00:14:29,868
That's all that Tantra is.

118
00:14:30,288 --> 00:14:35,543
It's just the transformation of that energy.

119
00:14:39,606 --> 00:15:01,918
it's just that understanding that all you're playing around with is some sort of energy force and that therefore through certain imagery and even through certain actions you can sublimate it, you can draw it out and take away that habit and what we want to do is get rid of that obsessiveness around these things so

120
00:15:03,147 --> 00:15:12,197
I'm sure you all know that, you know, if lust gets hold of us in a meditation retreat, it's got a tight hold, so you have to be very sharp on that.

121
00:15:13,038 --> 00:15:22,190
And remember that it can be an escape from something, a usual escape from anxiety, from loneliness, from all sorts of things.

122
00:15:24,211 --> 00:15:31,280
And romance, that delicious feeling that we get when we fall in love with somebody, you

123
00:15:31,884 --> 00:15:38,355
And the dreams and the books written, my goodness, and the films, I mean, it's just never ending.

124
00:15:38,375 --> 00:15:42,302
It's always the same plot, which is really annoying.

125
00:15:42,943 --> 00:15:47,191
It's always, but somehow, we still wring juice out of it.

126
00:15:47,370 --> 00:15:50,636
It doesn't matter how many romantic films people see, they love them.

127
00:15:52,298 --> 00:15:56,846
So it's that sheer deliciousness, isn't it, of being in love with somebody, you know?

128
00:15:58,597 --> 00:16:08,730
And again, I'm talking now about being in a meditation retreat, when the mind is wandering that day and it's fantasizing about, you know, some enchanted evening.

129
00:16:10,471 --> 00:16:15,138
And you're out there on, oh my good, you know, with old Frank Sinatra in the background.

130
00:16:15,158 --> 00:16:19,763
And you've got, and you have to see that immediately and go into it, you see.

131
00:16:19,743 --> 00:16:27,759
Now there'll be that deliciousness there because of the memory of the wanting to be at that place in that special way with another person.

132
00:16:27,980 --> 00:16:30,304
I mean, it is pure deliciousness.

133
00:16:30,586 --> 00:16:34,072
I can't think of anything more delicious myself.

134
00:16:34,205 --> 00:16:53,174
apart from maybe the jhanas and that's why you have to be slightly careful so remember that again there's always these two things it's delicious, we like to indulge in but it's also an escape it may be an escape, it doesn't have to be an escape

135
00:16:53,154 --> 00:17:09,560
may be an escape so when we're sitting here and we're beginning to be assailed by these romantic feelings and romantic dreams and you come back and you allow that feeling remember remember that feeling emotions all these things are all seeking metaphor

136
00:17:09,759 --> 00:17:11,182
They're all seeking metaphor.

137
00:17:11,201 --> 00:17:14,246
They're all seeking a way in which to express themselves.

138
00:17:14,266 --> 00:17:31,008
But when you just note romance, falling in love, and you note that and you turn away into the body and you feel the delicious feelings, as they begin to dissipate, don't be surprised if underneath it what you come across is a deep loneliness.

139
00:17:31,347 --> 00:17:32,730
Because that's what we're running from.

140
00:17:33,300 --> 00:17:51,798
so it's a case of remembering that so that when the loneliness comes up then there should be this little aha that's why I'm so obsessive about these romantic films and stuff it's because of this loneliness and of course you have to go into the loneliness you have to let the loneliness express itself

141
00:17:52,234 --> 00:17:57,540
You know, you are unlovable, nobody loves you, you're alone in this world, kill yourself.

142
00:17:57,560 --> 00:18:03,086
So you have to stay within those awful feelings, don't get caught up in those words.

143
00:18:03,606 --> 00:18:11,776
And then again, don't be surprised that as you sink into that loneliness, allow it, allow it to express itself and let it dissipate.

144
00:18:11,855 --> 00:18:16,240
Suddenly you're just sitting there in this really lovely state of solitude.

145
00:18:17,221 --> 00:18:19,743
You see, just being at one with oneself.

146
00:18:24,397 --> 00:18:25,800
It's a sense of lack, isn't it?

147
00:18:26,142 --> 00:18:27,964
There's a writer called David Loy.

148
00:18:28,306 --> 00:18:32,414
He can be a bit heavy because he's a very good philosopher.

149
00:18:33,135 --> 00:18:36,542
He's American.

150
00:18:36,623 --> 00:18:37,305
Works in Japan.

151
00:18:37,525 --> 00:18:40,571
And if you haven't come across his books, do look him up, David Loy.

152
00:18:40,832 --> 00:18:44,179
And he likes this word lack for dukkha.

153
00:18:44,310 --> 00:18:46,976
Not suffering, not unsatisfactoriness, but lack.

154
00:18:47,076 --> 00:18:48,577
There's a lack there.

155
00:18:49,159 --> 00:18:53,686
And when you think about it, that's just another way of saying desire, a wanting for something.

156
00:18:54,188 --> 00:18:56,791
And remember that the self is an empty thing.

157
00:18:57,432 --> 00:19:01,160
Not empty in the old Mahayana, the great emptiness.

158
00:19:01,460 --> 00:19:03,002
Emptiness ends up, there's nothing there.

159
00:19:03,063 --> 00:19:04,545
It's got to fill itself with something.

160
00:19:05,968 --> 00:19:07,230
Sex, drugs and rock and roll.

161
00:19:08,694 --> 00:19:17,548
So, again, it's a case of being very clear about what's happening there, you know, and to stop the mind.

162
00:19:18,087 --> 00:19:21,794
When I say stop the mind, you have to be careful not to back these things away.

163
00:19:22,193 --> 00:19:25,778
You're not trying to destroy the mind, you're not trying to kill it, you just note it.

164
00:19:26,019 --> 00:19:35,512
Now, as soon as you note what's going on, that which has been going on, the thought, the romance, it has to stop, because you can't think two thoughts at the same time.

165
00:19:35,662 --> 00:19:36,403
It's as simple as that.

166
00:19:36,624 --> 00:19:40,911
So if you keep saying, romance, romance, as soon as you've said that, the romance is gone.

167
00:19:42,574 --> 00:19:55,476
So what that means is that we've stopped with that noting, the acknowledgement, we've stopped the escape of this emotional energy from slipping up into these higher faculties to create this imaginary world, a virtual reality.

168
00:19:55,556 --> 00:19:56,116
That's what it is, eh?

169
00:19:57,538 --> 00:20:00,825
And if you get lost in that, then of course you tend to throw it out into the world.

170
00:20:02,559 --> 00:20:11,089
So by coming off those very patiently, just know that you come back into the heart and you just feel, feel what's going on there.

171
00:20:11,109 --> 00:20:18,617
And don't be surprised if suddenly, as it dissipates, some rather nasty feeling turns on.

172
00:20:18,637 --> 00:20:30,811
And of course, as those nasty feelings disappear, then there's nothing impelling this search for escape, happiness in romance and all these things, and therefore the obsessiveness begins to grow.

173
00:20:39,314 --> 00:20:45,905
And remember, as I keep saying, that all the energy we have, nothing is lost in this process.

174
00:20:46,185 --> 00:20:48,108
It is actually being slowly transformed.

175
00:20:48,349 --> 00:20:52,978
And all these things are transformed into love, compassion, joy, or peace.

176
00:20:53,980 --> 00:20:55,382
That's what we're doing.

177
00:21:02,585 --> 00:21:08,472
Now, you know, whenever I talk about this, especially as a monk, you know, everybody thinks, well, you know, he's just a monk.

178
00:21:08,913 --> 00:21:12,900
He's against the erotic and the romantic.

179
00:21:14,101 --> 00:21:18,907
He's taken about celibacy, so he's bitter.

180
00:21:20,770 --> 00:21:22,432
But it's not true.

181
00:21:25,113 --> 00:21:44,201
And if you think about the ordinary passage, I personally like the Brahminical path, because I think it's a bit, as usual, a bit male-dominated, but it is the way that you can see how the relationship between two people can lead to

182
00:21:44,923 --> 00:21:50,797
Ultimate renunciation and then finally a true love and then finally renunciation.

183
00:21:50,817 --> 00:21:56,910
So the idea is that you're a student until you're 25, thereabouts.

184
00:21:57,570 --> 00:22:00,176
Then you get married and you live the lay life.

185
00:22:00,196 --> 00:22:02,240
You live an involved life.

186
00:22:02,221 --> 00:22:06,967
And if possible you have a family, that's not necessary in this particular, in the spiritual sense.

187
00:22:07,587 --> 00:22:28,296
And during that time you go through, you know, a relationship and go through these particular moments where there's a block to be, there's a contradiction to be solved, a conflict to be solved, and in so doing the relationship gets closer and closer until there's what you might call a real union.

188
00:22:28,731 --> 00:22:34,484
And then around about the age of 65 or thereabouts, they're supposed to leave family.

189
00:22:34,545 --> 00:22:37,291
They're supposed to go away and live like hermits.

190
00:22:38,694 --> 00:22:44,428
And then at the age of 75, the man, and presumably the woman, we never talked about,

191
00:22:44,914 --> 00:22:47,240
The man disappears completely.

192
00:22:47,259 --> 00:22:52,792
He goes away, tries to lose his caste name.

193
00:22:53,193 --> 00:22:54,416
He's supposed to become a beggar.

194
00:22:54,758 --> 00:22:59,228
You're not supposed to approach him as an uncle or a father or anybody.

195
00:22:59,680 --> 00:23:04,865
And when you think about that, isn't that just the natural way of life?

196
00:23:05,566 --> 00:23:13,273
I mean, here you've got the leaves, and you can see it, the early buds, the full blossom, the slow dying, and then the disappearance.

197
00:23:13,913 --> 00:23:28,489
And so here you have the idea of a full life, if possible, you've got to have a bit of luck there, where, through meeting somebody, you form this very close, intimate relationship, which is very supportive,

198
00:23:29,026 --> 00:23:31,308
And we all know how difficult it is to get that.

199
00:23:31,729 --> 00:23:35,233
And then you work through that until it becomes utterly mature.

200
00:23:35,273 --> 00:23:38,919
Then there comes a time when you realize that even that has to be let go of.

201
00:23:39,720 --> 00:23:45,907
So remember, the spiritual path, whether we like it or not, eventually, at some point, is a path of renunciation.

202
00:23:47,890 --> 00:23:54,679
It's like, whether you like it or not, it's got to come that way.

203
00:23:57,763 --> 00:24:10,727
I heard Joseph Camberlain, some of you might know, the mythologist who wrote the book called Something of the Gods, and a very well-known writer.

204
00:24:11,167 --> 00:24:18,119
And he was interviewed on this and he was talking about two relationships that people sometimes go through.

205
00:24:18,160 --> 00:24:22,287
The first one being the worldly relationship and then a change in midlife.

206
00:24:22,267 --> 00:24:44,967
and then you finally find your spiritual partner and off you go and he reckoned that this was sort of a regular thing so there is within a relationship a real possibility of true spiritual friendship true spiritual growth and eventual the eventual path of renunciation which has to come at the end you see

207
00:24:45,807 --> 00:24:56,339
And talking about this, it's very interesting how people get a very negative view about marriage and things like that.

208
00:24:58,823 --> 00:25:07,173
I'm surprised how many Buddhists think that, for instance, it's not worth having children and bringing them into this life of suffering.

209
00:25:07,525 --> 00:25:24,807
And once a young man came to see me while I was in London, and he said that he was having problems with his relationship, which had been absolutely fine, but now she wanted kids, and he said he couldn't see the point because life is suffering, and he gave me all this stuff about suffering and pain.

210
00:25:24,886 --> 00:25:27,069
I thought, you know, why bring a child into this, you see?

211
00:25:28,788 --> 00:25:34,759
So I slowly argued that this was a very special place.

212
00:25:35,481 --> 00:25:43,518
That in fact it was right here that all the conditions are where a being can actually make very good, very quick spiritual progress.

213
00:25:43,557 --> 00:25:46,503
So I explained this to him.

214
00:25:47,105 --> 00:25:48,248
And then I said...

215
00:25:48,903 --> 00:26:08,157
Apart from becoming an Arahant, apart from becoming perhaps an Anagami, a non-returner, I can't see in the world anything more compassionate than to bring another being into this world and to give it that basic moral and spiritual teaching for its own growth.

216
00:26:10,082 --> 00:26:12,987
So he thanked me very much and I never saw him again.

217
00:26:16,779 --> 00:26:19,042
Which goes to show that he just didn't want kids.

218
00:26:22,207 --> 00:26:36,705
So I think we have to correct some of that because Buddhism has come to the West through the eyes of Christianity and it's still there as a life-negative religion.

219
00:26:37,646 --> 00:26:39,388
As a life-negating religion.

220
00:26:40,009 --> 00:26:41,311
And that's just not true.

221
00:26:41,592 --> 00:26:42,432
It's just not true.

222
00:26:45,214 --> 00:26:49,782
And then just finally within this sort of area is of course celibacy.

223
00:26:50,002 --> 00:26:53,788
And I'd like to coin a phrase from dear old Sir Winston Churchill.

224
00:26:54,931 --> 00:26:59,137
Some are born celibate.

225
00:26:59,157 --> 00:27:00,780
Some choose to be celibate.

226
00:27:01,803 --> 00:27:04,287
And some have celibacy thrust upon them.

227
00:27:07,709 --> 00:27:31,589
and we have to say that in the ordinary run of life we do find ourselves in celibate situations now for us as you know on the spiritual path those are times to get in contact with all the stuff around relationship around this sort of relationship

228
00:27:33,240 --> 00:27:35,087
Yes, and that's an opportunity.

229
00:27:35,127 --> 00:27:44,060
Remember, in daily life, here you see there's no point in getting into all these fantasies because it's really just taking out energy somewhere else.

230
00:27:44,480 --> 00:28:03,630
But in daily life, when we enter into daily life and these energies come up, and you can see there's no point in indulging them, then this idea of sublimation, of recognising that energy and then cajoling it, as it were, into some other area of activity.

231
00:28:06,093 --> 00:28:12,343
If one, of course, makes the decision that one wants a relationship, then have the faith, go with it, hope for the best.

232
00:28:16,053 --> 00:28:26,365
Just one last thing that I had slightly forgotten to mention is that I was very surprised once I did a talk at a marriage ceremony.

233
00:28:27,547 --> 00:28:28,488
Well, two things actually.

234
00:28:28,887 --> 00:28:31,691
A talk at a marriage ceremony, not for Buddhists.

235
00:28:31,711 --> 00:28:33,594
I was just a friend of this.

236
00:28:34,034 --> 00:28:34,894
Well, he was a Buddhist.

237
00:28:35,035 --> 00:28:35,576
Yeah, that's right.

238
00:28:35,816 --> 00:28:36,857
And everybody else wasn't.

239
00:28:37,838 --> 00:28:39,180
And I gave a talk.

240
00:28:39,401 --> 00:28:42,364
And in the talk, I simply mentioned the distinction between

241
00:28:42,614 --> 00:28:44,598
romantic feelings and real love.

242
00:28:45,561 --> 00:28:50,934
And I said that romantic feelings towards your partner just come and go.

243
00:28:51,036 --> 00:28:52,819
Sometimes you feel them and sometimes you don't.

244
00:28:53,722 --> 00:28:59,678
Often you feel hate, disgust, fed up, could get rid of the person, all that sort of stuff.

245
00:28:59,657 --> 00:29:03,001
And I said, but love, love has nothing to do with the emotional life.

246
00:29:03,122 --> 00:29:15,678
I said, love is to do with a commitment coming from a deeper centre that you have devoted your life to sharing your life with somebody else.

247
00:29:16,157 --> 00:29:18,320
And that is the underlying motivation.

248
00:29:18,800 --> 00:29:21,825
And if that goes, then definitely get a divorce.

249
00:29:23,606 --> 00:29:29,074
So I was surprised how many people came up to me afterwards and thanked me for that distinction.

250
00:29:30,151 --> 00:29:37,662
And I could only presume that in their own relationships they'd been utterly confused because they woke up in the morning and said, well, I don't love you.

251
00:29:37,682 --> 00:29:44,231
You sort of turn over and you see this person and you think, oh, God, 10 years, you know, what am I doing?

252
00:29:44,352 --> 00:29:47,717
And you think, I can't live, I've got to get out, I've got to find somebody else.

253
00:29:48,817 --> 00:29:51,281
And it's just that confusion about things, you know.

254
00:29:52,965 --> 00:30:03,070
And the other thing that I might say just on this little level is how I've conducted marriage ceremonies for people who've been in partnership for years.

255
00:30:03,392 --> 00:30:05,939
I mean, you know, 10, 15, 15 years.

256
00:30:07,402 --> 00:30:08,545
And

257
00:30:08,845 --> 00:30:20,486
All of them, and they tell me of friends who actually go through a marriage ceremony, that there is a distinctive difference once it moves into a state of vowing.

258
00:30:21,067 --> 00:30:29,300
Because when we make a public statement about our intentions, that really roots us very deeply in something.

259
00:30:29,280 --> 00:30:33,768
And that's why, you know, we take public oaths.

260
00:30:33,968 --> 00:30:37,794
That's why, say, when the president is elected, he makes a public oath.

261
00:30:38,394 --> 00:30:46,707
And that is a public commitment, and the whole of society is meant to be supportive, to support you with that.

262
00:30:46,727 --> 00:30:47,788
That's the idea of it.

263
00:30:48,308 --> 00:30:51,053
But that extra commitment...

264
00:30:51,589 --> 00:30:56,759
It just, as it were, deepened the whole relationship.

265
00:30:57,340 --> 00:31:01,710
Which means that in the partnership, there was always something holding back.

266
00:31:01,730 --> 00:31:03,133
Just something holding back.

267
00:31:03,272 --> 00:31:08,903
Just in case, after 10, 15 years, this is the wrong person to be with.

268
00:31:08,943 --> 00:31:10,307
Which would be very disappointing.

269
00:31:11,823 --> 00:31:16,371
After 15 years you suddenly decide this is not the person I ought to have been with.

270
00:31:17,373 --> 00:31:27,250
So just remembering all that and remembering that here in our meditation to be very quick with those thoughts because they are, they're delicious.

271
00:31:35,481 --> 00:31:36,743
Yes, celibacy.

272
00:31:37,384 --> 00:31:47,118
So the idea of when we find ourselves in a celibate situation is that this is a time to allow those things to pass away.

273
00:31:47,779 --> 00:32:02,079
And again, this sublimation so that we can see that times of celibacy and for monastics, the idea is to refine that energy, to take it away from there and to actually refine it, you see.

274
00:32:03,173 --> 00:32:04,074
That's the idea of that.

275
00:32:04,153 --> 00:32:06,416
And it's displaced into the spiritual path.

276
00:32:15,209 --> 00:32:18,894
I think I've just got a bit of time, I think, to talk about attachment.

277
00:32:19,816 --> 00:32:23,480
So this is also a love with a little kink in it.

278
00:32:24,301 --> 00:32:28,326
And just think of all the people whom we are attached to.

279
00:32:28,367 --> 00:32:30,210
You know, children...

280
00:32:30,680 --> 00:32:34,426
family, friends, even animals.

281
00:32:36,369 --> 00:32:39,395
You can love an animal as much as you can love a human being.

282
00:32:41,239 --> 00:32:43,623
And there's an attachment to it.

283
00:32:44,905 --> 00:32:54,442
And the unfortunate thing is that we don't know the depth of the attachment until the beloved disappears.

284
00:32:55,029 --> 00:32:57,844
You don't know how attached you are to your cat until it dies.

285
00:32:58,467 --> 00:33:02,105
You don't know how attached you are to your mother until she dies.

286
00:33:02,527 --> 00:33:03,571
I can tell you that.

287
00:33:04,852 --> 00:33:07,615
And this is one of those things that we don't really know.

288
00:33:07,654 --> 00:33:13,401
Now, the only distinction I like to make is that we're not here talking about something evil.

289
00:33:14,102 --> 00:33:15,123
We're not talking about something evil.

290
00:33:15,163 --> 00:33:17,105
We're talking about something unskillful.

291
00:33:17,665 --> 00:33:29,458
When the Buddha uses the word akusala, see there's two words in the Pali, papa, which means evil, and akusala, which just simply means unskillful, unwholesome, not virtuous.

292
00:33:29,928 --> 00:33:56,407
and in terms of the path we're just trying to shift all our conditionings towards the virtuous so it's not a case of feeling guilty about attachment it's a case of knowing that there is some attachment there that there has to be some attachment there and say within parents you see that's the rebellious teenager they just want to get away from that grip that hold and

293
00:33:58,430 --> 00:34:06,799
And of course the root reason for that is that we're seeking happiness in human beings.

294
00:34:08,402 --> 00:34:10,384
Now that's ridiculous.

295
00:34:10,503 --> 00:34:15,349
Anything in the world to depend upon for happiness is definitely not a human being.

296
00:34:15,369 --> 00:34:17,733
I mean, that's really awful.

297
00:34:18,172 --> 00:34:20,556
I mean, they leave you, then they hate you.

298
00:34:21,885 --> 00:34:23,809
And then they die on you, for heaven's sake.

299
00:34:24,251 --> 00:34:31,063
I mean, there's no way that, you know, when you think about it, you'd want your happiness to be dependent on a yin-bing.

300
00:34:31,083 --> 00:34:33,248
I mean, rather a rock.

301
00:34:33,268 --> 00:34:34,610
That will stay there for a while.

302
00:34:34,630 --> 00:34:36,675
I mean, you know, I should outlive you.

303
00:34:36,735 --> 00:34:39,922
You know, you can keep hugging the rock.

304
00:34:40,322 --> 00:34:40,782
Or a tree.

305
00:34:41,425 --> 00:34:41,925
Love a tree.

306
00:34:41,985 --> 00:34:43,168
That's much better.

307
00:34:43,351 --> 00:34:46,114
But a human being is very, very fickle.

308
00:34:46,135 --> 00:34:56,750
So once we see that, you see, and we take the attachment away, and then the confusion disappears between what attachment is and what love is.

309
00:34:58,492 --> 00:34:59,875
And just to be aware of that.

310
00:34:59,894 --> 00:35:03,960
And of course the downside of attachment is that the person becomes an object.

311
00:35:04,440 --> 00:35:09,949
They become something to satisfy your lack.

312
00:35:10,063 --> 00:35:16,432
That's what an attachment does, you know, I want you to be like this, I want you to grow up like this, you know, to get angry.

313
00:35:17,353 --> 00:35:32,054
And you can see in certain behaviours, for instance, supposing, you know, you were told or somebody was told that the doctor said to them that they had terminal cancer.

314
00:35:32,795 --> 00:35:42,590
And when the doctor sort of told them that, they begin to break down and weep and cry, gnash their teeth, bang the table, how terrible it is and all that.

315
00:35:42,610 --> 00:35:44,472
You think, well, that's very unprofessional.

316
00:35:44,492 --> 00:35:47,135
I don't expect the doctor to do that, you see.

317
00:35:48,018 --> 00:35:58,313
And you expect them to be compassionate, kind, softly spoken, but, you know, just, as we say, with you in that quiet way.

318
00:35:58,545 --> 00:36:05,534
And when you go home and you say to your partner, I've got terminal cancer, and they reply, well, what do you want to wear in the coffin?

319
00:36:06,617 --> 00:36:08,318
And you think, my goodness, don't you love me?

320
00:36:08,579 --> 00:36:12,565
I expect you to weep gnashing of teeth and all that sort of stuff.

321
00:36:12,585 --> 00:36:17,311
And so you can see how behaviours change when that attachment comes.

322
00:36:18,012 --> 00:36:21,295
And it's a case of just recognising that.

323
00:36:21,315 --> 00:36:26,443
With children, you see, you can see parents, if the child hurts itself...

324
00:36:26,422 --> 00:36:30,989
And it's just a scratch and the parent knows it's just a little thing, you see.

325
00:36:31,188 --> 00:36:32,451
But the kid's screaming, you see.

326
00:36:33,090 --> 00:36:38,237
The parent's very calm, very quiet, hugs the child, everything's all right, all that sort of stuff.

327
00:36:38,257 --> 00:36:45,786
But if the parent sees that the child has actually broken a leg or really banged his head and, oh my goodness, then the fear comes out and all that.

328
00:36:45,806 --> 00:36:50,472
And of course that feeds right into the child and the child becomes the object of fear.

329
00:36:50,452 --> 00:36:55,619
The poor kid's trying to handle all this pain and the mother or father's berserkness.

330
00:36:57,001 --> 00:36:59,346
But it's just part and parcel of that relationship.

331
00:37:04,813 --> 00:37:17,210
So, if we find ourselves here in the meditation, you see, wanting to phone somebody, expecting somebody to phone them, wanting to get in touch with some family member, some friend, you see.

332
00:37:17,652 --> 00:37:20,054
If you see that, that's a product of attachment.

333
00:37:21,452 --> 00:37:22,615
Just let it pass, let it pass.

334
00:37:23,277 --> 00:37:27,427
And then there might be that feeling of guilt, of some sort of loss of love, you see.

335
00:37:28,971 --> 00:37:35,967
Because there's that confusion between what love is and what that attachment is.

336
00:37:41,297 --> 00:37:44,103
I've got time just for one more thing I wanted to... Oh, yeah.

337
00:37:46,489 --> 00:37:50,335
And just to take the deliciousness to that other area of distraction.

338
00:37:50,637 --> 00:37:52,981
So be careful, especially on a retreat, you see.

339
00:37:53,563 --> 00:37:56,668
We might think to ourselves, oh, it would be nice to go for a walk now.

340
00:37:57,269 --> 00:37:58,773
I think I feel I need a walk.

341
00:37:59,213 --> 00:38:01,077
But actually, if you sit with that...

342
00:38:01,177 --> 00:38:02,641
actually just fed up with being inside.

343
00:38:03,222 --> 00:38:04,726
You're just trying to escape being inside.

344
00:38:05,108 --> 00:38:10,284
Or you don't want to walk up and down the same walking path anymore.

345
00:38:10,304 --> 00:38:13,211
You want to have a distraction, do it somewhere else.

346
00:38:13,461 --> 00:38:28,896
And if you can really let that go, and as it were, draw the space around you closer, making your boundary less and less, you'll see it has a great force on your meditation and your stillness.

347
00:38:29,476 --> 00:38:31,621
Because every time you wander off on a walk,

348
00:38:32,463 --> 00:38:33,244
You're in a different place.

349
00:38:33,545 --> 00:38:34,728
You're exciting something.

350
00:38:34,788 --> 00:38:35,648
Something's arising.

351
00:38:36,170 --> 00:38:37,032
And it's very difficult.

352
00:38:37,773 --> 00:38:44,648
I'm sure you've all experienced, so we say, even doing quick walking as an exercise, how suddenly the mind will start wandering.

353
00:38:45,528 --> 00:38:49,257
And you've walked up and down for ten minutes and you've been everywhere and anywhere.

354
00:38:50,097 --> 00:38:53,682
So all these desires for distraction, you see.

355
00:38:54,244 --> 00:39:13,353
So remember that if we really want to get to know the mind and to really get into its turbulences, if we really want to squeeze the pimple, as it were, then you've got to, as it were, stop the input.

356
00:39:13,485 --> 00:39:14,447
That's the point, you see.

357
00:39:14,708 --> 00:39:15,791
You've got to stop the input.

358
00:39:15,811 --> 00:39:18,237
You've got to stop looking, stop listening.

359
00:39:18,518 --> 00:39:19,902
Hearing is different from listening.

360
00:39:21,646 --> 00:39:30,447
And as soon as you stop the input, then there's no way these turbulences can find a way to express themselves.

361
00:39:30,867 --> 00:39:31,126
See?

362
00:39:31,407 --> 00:39:33,869
And the mind starts going berserk, but you keep playing with it.

363
00:39:33,949 --> 00:39:36,512
And when that's cut off, what can they do?

364
00:39:36,532 --> 00:39:41,097
All these griefs, guilt, fear, the whole gamut of human suffering.

365
00:39:41,557 --> 00:39:42,958
It booms out as it comes out.

366
00:39:42,978 --> 00:39:45,342
It comes out as these awful, awful, terrible feelings.

367
00:39:45,402 --> 00:39:46,563
But that's the purification.

368
00:39:47,003 --> 00:39:47,643
That's purgatory.

369
00:39:50,847 --> 00:39:51,668
Just hang on in there.

370
00:39:53,570 --> 00:39:55,411
And just keep saying to yourself, there is an end to suffering.

371
00:39:55,431 --> 00:39:55,771
There is.

372
00:39:56,672 --> 00:39:57,634
There's got to be.

373
00:39:59,739 --> 00:40:09,614
So that's why in meditation we're always encouraged to go inward, to stay with what's happening within ourselves.

374
00:40:12,016 --> 00:40:15,862
And just as an addenda to all that, of course, is the problem of boredom.

375
00:40:16,623 --> 00:40:22,733
So remember, boredom is that frustration, is that getting fed up with distraction and pleasure.

376
00:40:22,753 --> 00:40:28,701
So be very careful with boredom, because boredom will tell you to seek distraction, to do something else.

377
00:40:28,681 --> 00:40:35,929
Remember that the whole point of the pleasure syndrome is that there's an inbuilt obsolescence.

378
00:40:35,989 --> 00:40:38,673
You can't keep chewing the same sweet.

379
00:40:38,893 --> 00:40:39,534
It gets boring.

380
00:40:39,554 --> 00:40:41,958
You've got to go for the raspberry flavour or the coffee flavour.

381
00:40:42,539 --> 00:40:48,867
You've got to move a little bit to get that same sense of pleasure or joy out of it.

382
00:40:48,847 --> 00:40:57,420
So whenever boredom comes up, you see, you feel the boredom, you don't get confused by boredom on the breath, boredom on this, boredom on that, boredom with food.

383
00:40:58,362 --> 00:40:59,804
You stay with the boredom, you see.

384
00:41:00,465 --> 00:41:06,396
And the way to overcome boredom is to keep doing what you're doing, repetition.

385
00:41:06,677 --> 00:41:12,465
Just repetition and keeping in mind, keeping that boredom, as it were, within your attentiveness.

386
00:41:13,007 --> 00:41:14,769
And then don't be surprised.

387
00:41:14,750 --> 00:41:39,306
if the boredom suddenly disappears and what arises is its opposite which is interest only this time because you've let the boredom go some wrong purpose has been got rid of that's the point boredom has come because we're seeking happiness in whatever it is we're experiencing

388
00:41:40,400 --> 00:41:52,902
I mean, our society is really bad with that because pleasure is so easy at hand and we expect to be distracted, we expect to be entertained all the time, TV, radio, the whole thing.

389
00:41:53,905 --> 00:42:00,416
And to enter into a place where there's nothing, then you get this boredom arising.

390
00:42:01,190 --> 00:42:09,739
And going back to the Buddha's own experience, remember, after he had become enlightened for seven years, Mara stalked him with his three daughters.

391
00:42:10,860 --> 00:42:15,885
Sexual desire, pleasure and boredom.

392
00:42:15,905 --> 00:42:16,425
See?

393
00:42:16,445 --> 00:42:20,610
So there's little boys saying, this is really boring just sitting here, why don't you get on with it?

394
00:42:22,672 --> 00:42:29,019
So, with that in mind, be careful of these delicious areas.

395
00:42:30,856 --> 00:42:36,563
So I think there's just some time to complete some of these questions.

396
00:42:36,704 --> 00:42:40,028
Now, unfortunately, I lost the list.

397
00:42:40,068 --> 00:42:46,958
I brought the wrong list that I was working with last week, but I shall answer a few more next week.

398
00:42:46,998 --> 00:42:51,885
Let me just give some indications to these.

399
00:42:54,311 --> 00:43:12,101
can you please discuss the differences in practices and goals in the Theravada, Zen, Dzogchen and Vajrayana tradition well the way that I think you'll find eventually people who have practiced so we say even two, three or four of these is that

400
00:43:12,081 --> 00:43:14,846
The only difference is skillful means, that's all.

401
00:43:15,106 --> 00:43:21,976
We're just using always skillful means, some different ways in order to achieve the same end.

402
00:43:22,356 --> 00:43:23,619
What is that end, you see?

403
00:43:23,958 --> 00:43:27,664
It's sati, right awareness and panya, insight.

404
00:43:27,684 --> 00:43:28,266
That's all it is.

405
00:43:28,786 --> 00:43:34,815
And either you get it by observing the phenomena of the mind,

406
00:43:35,081 --> 00:43:45,233
in other words, which is more Theravada-based, or, as it were, you become aware more of the space within which this is happening, which is that consciousness.

407
00:43:46,054 --> 00:43:51,442
And just that begins to separate consciousness out from the contents that it sees within itself.

408
00:43:52,302 --> 00:43:53,184
So it doesn't matter.

409
00:43:53,324 --> 00:43:59,030
Even in Theravada one becomes aware of the knowing as a different faculty from everything it knows.

410
00:43:59,702 --> 00:44:28,123
so remember that all these traditions arose as they passed through cultures and even in our culture now you can see the effect of western psychotherapy on the practice of the Basler and it's bound to happen and it's a good thing because that's the way we are please discuss the pros and cons of being in the breath of the nostrils as opposed to the abdomen

411
00:44:28,929 --> 00:44:47,952
the general or the usual instruction is you watch the breath where you feel it most and that's the important thing because it's your primary object it's something you want to go back to it's something that you want to develop a certain stillness with because I don't use the word concentration

412
00:44:48,353 --> 00:45:03,981
and it's something which, when everything quietens down, the still mind, the peaceful heart, and the quiet body, or the quiet mind, still body, there is only the breath, and that becomes the object which you are looking at.

413
00:45:04,280 --> 00:45:09,771
So, keeping that in mind, that the primary object is supposed to be the breath,

414
00:45:10,088 --> 00:45:38,813
and at the point where you feel it most I think you generally agree with me those of you who've tried both is that when you watch the breath of the nostrils you tend to lose the body it's a very good technique for concentration meditations because you don't have to worry about the body you become concentrated up here whereas when you stay down at the abdomen you're as it were buried in the body you tend to feel more in contact with the body

415
00:45:39,990 --> 00:45:50,693
The other thing is that in the Mahasi tradition, of course, the rising and falling of the abdomen is then carried into the rising and falling of the footstep.

416
00:45:50,791 --> 00:46:01,168
So that this constant awareness of transience, arising and falling, beginning, ending, beginning, ending, radical ending, full stop, something arising.

417
00:46:01,849 --> 00:46:12,646
And so if we use the abdomen and the rising and falling of the footstep, there is just that constant pointing of the attention at the quality of anicca.

418
00:46:12,947 --> 00:46:16,835
Of course it still works at the nostrils because the breath is coming in, stopping, going out.

419
00:46:17,195 --> 00:46:24,670
But it's not so obvious as this rising and falling of the abdomen and the rising and falling of the footstep.

420
00:46:25,413 --> 00:46:30,643
But in the end it's really up to a person and where they feel also most comfortable.

421
00:46:30,943 --> 00:46:33,588
The Mahasi himself was not strict.

422
00:46:33,608 --> 00:46:35,192
He started off with touch points.

423
00:46:36,302 --> 00:46:41,367
And he just ended up with the belly and that became the focus of most teachings.

424
00:46:41,387 --> 00:46:55,219
It was only I think later teachers who insisted on watching the abdomen.

425
00:46:55,239 --> 00:46:59,302
So I hope my words have been of some assistance.

426
00:46:59,322 --> 00:47:05,347
May you be liberated from all suffering even by the weekend.

